<paper id="1608865483"><title>On Estimating the Size of Projections</title><year>1990</year><authors><author org="University of Wisconsin-Madison" id="2075622585">Jeffrey F. Naughton</author><author org="University of Wisconsin-Madison" id="2707131050">S. Seshadri</author></authors><n_citation>36</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1513100972</reference><reference>1587364696</reference><reference>1968829657</reference><reference>1972223681</reference><reference>1988144572</reference><reference>1991782662</reference><reference>2008365755</reference><reference>2021705190</reference><reference>2025051251</reference><reference>2048341095</reference><reference>2154165046</reference><reference>2168447405</reference><reference>2197881366</reference></references><venue id="1165285842" type="C">International Conference on Database Theory</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-53507-1_98</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.61926">Ramer–Douglas–Peucker algorithm</keyword><keyword weight="0.46315">Experimental data</keyword><keyword weight="0.546">Tuple</keyword><keyword weight="0.44646">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.46236">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.60699">Sampling (statistics)</keyword><keyword weight="0.57779">Gibbs sampling</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>We present a new sampling algorithm for estimating the number of tuples in the projection of a relation. The algorithm requires no assumptions about the distributions of values in the attributes of the relation and converges faster and smoother than previous sampling algorithms for the problem. We give both a sound theoretical basis for the algorithm and experimental data from an implementation of the algorithm.</abstract></paper>